Proper MVL: Fast Automation Runtime for Chrome on macOS

Goal of the MVL

Complete real tasks in predictable time by:
	•	keeping the browser/session warm
	•	using bounded retries + explicit timeouts
	•	using state-based waits (DOM conditions), not “sleep” or networkidle
	•	pushing micro-logic into a local executor, not the LLM

⸻

1) What we build (stack)

A) Local Automation Runtime (your app)

Runs on the Mac and provides:
	•	a persistent Chrome connection
	•	a fast DOM controller
	•	an executor that runs actions until success/fail with strict limits
	•	logs + replay

B) MCP Server layer (tool interface for Codex)

Exposes smart tools like press, type_into, wait_for, extract_table.

Codex calls one tool per meaningful action, not 50 tiny steps.

C) Browser control method

For speed + reliability:
	•	CDP directly (fast, thin)
	•	or Playwright but with strict rules (persistent context, no networkidle)

If Playwright felt “forever,” it’s usually because it’s being used in “test defaults” mode. This MVL forces a “robot mode.”

⸻

2) The key design: “Executor runs, model plans”

Bad (slow forever)

LLM does:
	1.	screenshot / read
	2.	decide
	3.	click
	4.	wait
	5.	repeat…

Good (fast)

LLM does:
	•	“Do X on site Y”

Your runtime does (locally):
	•	locate → click/type → verify → retry → timeout → return result

This alone prevents “forever.”

⸻

3) Tools (minimal but powerful)

session_start(profile="automation")
	•	Ensures Chrome is running once
	•	Attaches to existing automation profile
	•	Returns session_id

navigate(url)
	•	Fast navigation with a max timeout (e.g. 10s)
	•	Returns final URL + title

press(target)

Target can be:
	•	selector: css=button[type=submit]
	•	text: text=Sign in
	•	role+name: {role:"button", name:"Sign in"}

Executor rules:
	•	try cached locator first
	•	else search by priority list
	•	click
	•	verify via condition (below)
	•	1 retry with broader search
	•	then fail with a structured error

type_into(target, text, clear=true)
	•	focus field
	•	set value (not slow key-by-key unless needed)
	•	verify field value changed

wait_for(condition, timeout_ms)

Conditions allowed:
	•	selector visible/hidden
	•	URL matches regex
	•	text appears
	•	spinner disappears
	•	network request finished (optional, targeted)

Rule: never wait for networkidle globally.

extract(target, format)
	•	reads text/table/json from DOM
	•	returns structured output

screenshot(region?) (debug only)

Not in the core loop; used only when failing.

⸻

4) The “ADAS-style” internal loop (the part that stops forever)

Every tool call runs a bounded state machine:

Example: press("text=Download")

Budget: 800ms locate, 200ms click, 2s verify (configurable)
	1.	Locate (<= 800ms total)
	•	if cached locator works → use it (5–20ms)
	•	else query DOM for best match (10–60ms)
	•	else scroll small amount and retry locate once (optional)
	2.	Act (<= 200ms)
	•	DOM click (CDP dispatchMouseEvent or element.click)
	3.	Verify (<= 2000ms)
	•	wait for one of:
	•	URL changed
	•	download event fired
	•	element disappeared
	•	success toast appears
	•	new panel visible
	4.	Retry (max 1)
	•	broaden locator strategy (text fuzzy, role fallback)
	•	if still fails → return error with:
	•	what it tried
	•	why verify failed
	•	page url/title
	•	optional screenshot

Hard stop: after the timeout, it returns. No infinite waiting.

⸻

5) Why Playwright “takes forever” and how MVL fixes it

Common causes and the fix baked into MVL:
	•	Launching browser each task → MVL: persistent profile/session
	•	waitUntil: networkidle → MVL: only wait for UI conditions
	•	LLM in micro-loop → MVL: executor handles micro-steps
	•	no success condition → MVL: every action has verification rules
	•	global timeouts too large → MVL: strict per-step budgets
	•	selectors unstable → MVL: locator strategy stack + caching

⸻

6) Deliverables (what “proper MVL” means as output)

Day-1 MVL demo tasks

Pick any 2–3 and make them rock-solid:
	1.	Login → go to dashboard → export CSV
	2.	Fill form → submit → confirm success message
	3.	Search → open result → copy table data

Required observability (non-negotiable)
	•	timeline log per action:
	•	locate_ms, act_ms, verify_ms, retries
	•	store last DOM snapshot snippet (small)
	•	optional last screenshot only on failure

This is how you debug speed.

⸻

7) What you should build first (concrete order)
	1.	session_start with persistent Chrome profile
	2.	navigate + wait_for(url/selector)
	3.	press + type_into with strict timeouts + verification
	4.	cache locators (store best selector per site+action)
	5.	failure report (why stuck, what tried)
	6.	Only then add “smart planning” prompts for Codex/Claude

⸻

A simple rule that makes it fast

If an action can’t be verified in 2 seconds, return control to the model with a structured error.
That’s how you avoid “forever.”

⸻

If you tell me one real task you want as the MVL (example: “login to X and download report Y”), I’ll turn it into:
	•	the exact action graph (steps + success conditions)
	•	the exact tool calls and verification checks
	•	the timeout budget per step (so it never hangs)